ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescent signal of A-Dots, which was significantly exceeding the background fluorescent level, was detected in the producer P3 at about 60 days after the nanoagent injection (Fig. 6
                        ). The intensity of A-Dots fluorescence has been increasing for almost a year, with a peak at about 345 days and another at 581 days since injection time, thereafter confirming the breakthrough. These double peaks are likely due to water injection shutdown as explained below, and not an indication of water flow along two different paths toward P3. The actual amount of A-Dots in the produced water was determined by employing calibration curves built using samples of the original injection solution stored in screw-cap pressure tubes at 100 °C for the entire duration of the test to account for possible alterations of fluorescent intensity caused by reactions of the nanoagent with hot water. The resulting recovery curve (Fig. 6) was compared to the recovery curves of chemical tracers (labeled here as Tracer A and B) deployed earlier in same well as reported in Sanni et al. (2015). Whereas the overall shape of the curves and the position of their maxima were similar, the A-Dots recovery showed two pronounced dips at 525 and 777 days after the nanoagent injection and it also had persistent fluctuations of considerable magnitude not seen with the chemical tracers. Fluctuations in the concentrations may be associated with sorption, and then desorption, of A-Dots at favorable attachment sites within the pore spaces. The reader is referred to our previous publication (Kanj et al., 2011) for further details on A-Dots interactions within the flow medium. A possible explanation for the dips was found in the water injection log of I3 as the injection has been stopped for several weeks on two separate occasions as shown in Fig. 7
                        . The minima on the recovery curve occurred approximately 10 months after the injection rate has been temporarily dropped to zero at two different times. The injection rates are shown as monthly averages because of very large variation in daily injection rates making the data inconvenient for visual analysis.
